---

<Record
  title={title}
  description={description}
  tower="Tower 02"
  name="Amadeus"
  lede="He talks. The coding agents get a workspace."
  accent="cyan"
  github="https://github.com/MattisEngelhardt/Amadeus-Local-AI-Handoff-Agent"
  next={{ href: '/city/papers', label: 'Tower 03 — The Paper Mill' }}
>
  <section class="act">
    <h2>The brief</h2>
    <p>
      The bottleneck with coding agents is not the coding — it is the
      context. Amadeus attacks exactly that: raw input (voice notes,
      Telegram messages, files, links, half-formed project sketches)
      goes in, and what comes out is an execution-ready workspace that
      a downstream agent — Claude Code, Codex — can pick up and run
      with. Amadeus writes no production code itself. It makes sure
      whoever does has everything.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="act">
    <h2>How it runs</h2>
    <p>
      Ten steps, fully local: capture preserves the original material
      and its metadata; audio is transcribed on-device; a master prompt
      is drafted; a gap analysis asks the blocking questions before
      anything proceeds; everything converts to agent-readable
      Markdown; a readiness gate validates the package — and only then
      is the workspace built and handed off as files, not as live
      agent control.
    </p>
    <p>
      A finished workspace reads like a project briefing written by a
      careful chief of staff: CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, a master prompt,
      requirements, decision records, next steps, a source map — plus
      the original sources, indexed.
    </p>
    <p class="aside">
      The idea has a name: voice-to-context. Production code is cheap
      now; well-prepared intent is not.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="act">
    <h2>Honest status</h2>
    <p>
      Verified working end-to-end for text input and workspace
      generation, all on local models. Telegram ingestion and
      persistent state are still in progress — this record will be
      updated when they land.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="act">
    <h2>Stack</h2>
    <p class="stack mono-label">
      Python &middot; Ollama (Gemma) &middot; faster-whisper large-v3
      &middot; Telegram &middot; Markdown handoff
    </p>
  </section>
</Record>
